            <section class="prose mt-8">
              <h2>How this concrete calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                This tool computes the volume of concrete needed for common
                shapes using standard geometric formulas, then converts that
                volume into cubic yards, cubic meters and approximate premix bag
                counts.
              </p>

              <h3>1. Volume formulas</h3>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p><strong>Rectangular slab / footing / wall</strong></p>
                <p>\( V = L \times W \times T \)</p>
                <p>where:</p>
                <ul>
                  <li>\(L\) = length</li>
                  <li>\(W\) = width</li>
                  <li>\(T\) = thickness (or height for a wall)</li>
                </ul>
                <p><strong>Cylindrical column / tube</strong></p>
                <p>\( V = \pi r^2 h \)</p>
                <p>where \(r\) is radius and \(h\) is height.</p>
                <p><strong>Stairs (approximation)</strong></p>
                <p>We approximate the stair run as a right triangular prism:</p>
                <p>
                  \( V = \tfrac{1}{2} \times \text{run} \times \text{rise}
                  \times \text{width} \)
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>2. Unit conversions</h3>
              <p>
                The calculator automatically converts all dimensions to a
                consistent unit (feet or meters) before computing volume.
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <ul>
                  <li>1 ft = 12 in</li>
                  <li>1 yd = 3 ft</li>
                  <li>1 m = 100 cm</li>
                  <li>1 ft³ = 0.037037 yd³ (1 yd³ = 27 ft³)</li>
                  <li>1 m³ ≈ 35.3147 ft³</li>
                </ul>
              </div>

              <h3>3. Waste / overage</h3>
              <p>
                Real jobs rarely match the exact theoretical volume. To account
                for spillage, uneven subgrade and minor measurement errors,
                contractors typically add 5–10% extra concrete.
              </p>
              <p>The calculator applies your waste factor as:</p>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p>
                  \( V_\text{final} = V_\text{raw} \times (1 + \tfrac{w}{100})
                  \)
                </p>
                <p>where \(w\) is the waste percentage.</p>
              </div>

              <h3>4. Bag yield assumptions</h3>
              <p>
                Premix bag yields are approximate and can vary by brand and mix
                design. This calculator uses typical values:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <ul>
                  <li>40 lb bag ≈ 0.30 ft³</li>
                  <li>60 lb bag ≈ 0.45 ft³</li>
                  <li>80 lb bag ≈ 0.60 ft³</li>
                  <li>20 kg bag ≈ 0.009 m³</li>
                  <li>25 kg bag ≈ 0.011 m³</li>
                  <li>30 kg bag ≈ 0.013 m³</li>
                </ul>
              </div>
              <p>Number of bags is then:</p>
              <p>\( \text{bags} = \dfrac{V}{\text{yield per bag}} \)</p>

              <h3>5. Estimating concrete weight</h3>
              <p>
                If you enter a density, the calculator multiplies the final
                volume by that density to estimate total weight.
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p>
                  <strong>Imperial:</strong> \( W = V_\text{ft³} \times
                  \rho_{\text{lb/ft³}} \)
                </p>
                <p>
                  <strong>Metric:</strong> \( W = V_\text{m³} \times
                  \rho_{\text{kg/m³}} \)
                </p>
              </div>

              <h2>Worked example: 10×10 slab, 4 inches thick</h2>
              <ol>
                <li>Convert thickness: 4 in ÷ 12 = 0.333 ft.</li>
                <li>
                  Volume in ft³: \(10 \times 10 \times 0.333 ≈ 33.3\) ft³.
                </li>
                <li>Convert to yd³: \(33.3 ÷ 27 ≈ 1.23\) yd³.</li>
                <li>Add 10% waste: \(1.23 × 1.10 ≈ 1.35\) yd³.</li>
                <li>
                  80 lb bags: 1.35 yd³ × 27 ft³/yd³ ÷ 0.60 ft³/bag ≈ 61 bags.
                </li>
              </ol>

              <h2>Practical tips for ordering concrete</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Round up</strong> to the next 0.25–0.5 yd³ when
                  ordering ready-mix.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Check truck capacity</strong> (often 8–10 yd³) for
                  large pours.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Prepare the subgrade</strong> (compacted, level, damp
                  but not muddy) before the truck arrives.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Have help ready</strong> – concrete sets quickly,
                  especially in hot weather.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2 id="faq">Concrete calculator FAQ</h2>
              <h3>How accurate is this concrete calculator?</h3>
              <p>
                The math is exact for the dimensions you enter, but site
                conditions introduce uncertainty. Always verify measurements on
                site and add a reasonable waste factor.
              </p>

              <h3>Should I use bags or order ready-mix?</h3>
              <p>
                Hand-mixing bags is practical for small projects (typically
                under 1–1.5 yd³). For larger slabs, walls or multiple piers,
                ready-mix delivery is usually faster, more consistent and often
                cheaper overall.
              </p>

              <h3>What thickness should my concrete slab be?</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>Sidewalks &amp; patios: typically 4 in (100 mm)</li>
                <li>Driveways: 4–5 in (100–125 mm)</li>
                <li>Garage floors: 4–6 in (100–150 mm)</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Always follow local building codes and, for structural work, a
                licensed engineer’s design.
              </p>
            </section>
